;; ch14-playable-poetry.book.slatl
;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 14: Playable Poetry

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      14
  :title               "Playable Poetry"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"A game can be a poem. There are no rules against this. The runtime
does not know the difference between a shooter and a haiku; you can
build either.

This chapter is for things that are not games. Playable poems.
Interactive elegies. Small experiences that live for two minutes and
are done. The kid presses a key; a line arrives. She presses another;
the line settles. She sits with it. She presses again. Another line.

No score. No branches. No goal. Just pacing — the reader controls
the pace, and the pace IS the piece.

The physics of tempo: text arrival is a small motion. Motion has
feel. Feel is how a poem lands.

---

## 14.1 A first poem

```scheme
(define poem
  '(\"The kitchen at dawn.\"
    \"Something on the stove.\"
    \"A jar of honey with a spoon in it.\"
    \"Someone was here and left in a hurry.\"
    \"You do not know when they will come back.\"
    \"You wait.\"))

(define (play-poem)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (let loop ((lines poem) (i 0))
    (when (not (null? lines))
      (motion/drop-line (car lines) 40 (+ 40 (* i 60)))
      (loop (cdr lines) (+ i 1)))))

(define (motion/drop-line text x y)
  ;; Text arrives from above, easing into place.
  (paint-text x y text :y-offset -20)
  (motion/drop 'a-text-slot :duration 45 :ease 'ease-out))
```

Six lines. Each drops from above. Each settles. The kid presses SPACE
between lines to advance.

`motion/drop` is a text-arrival verb. The line appears twenty pixels
above its target, then eases down. Forty-five frames — three-quarters
of a second. The line lands like a leaf.

The whole poem is thirty seconds if the kid reads at a natural pace,
or five minutes if she stops between each line to think. Either is
fine. The poem is the pace she chooses.

---

## 14.2 Pace as gameplay

The player controls the pace with a single button.

```scheme
;; A line-by-line reader with player-controlled pace.
(define (poem-reader lines)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (let ((idx 0))
    (define (show-line)
      (when (< idx (length lines))
        (let ((line (list-ref lines idx))
              (y (+ 40 (* idx 60))))
          (paint-text-with-drop line 40 y)
          (set! idx (+ idx 1)))))
    ;; Show the first line automatically.
    (show-line)
    ;; Each SPACE press shows the next.
    (on-key
      (lambda (k)
        (when (eq? k 'space) (show-line))))))
```

The reader presses SPACE. The next line arrives. She can wait as long
as she wants between presses. If she reads fast, the poem is fast. If
she reads slow, the poem breathes.

This is the whole game. No branches. No score. Just the reader
controlling when the next line comes.

Now change one thing: what if SOME lines linger and SOME lines fade?

---

## 14.3 Lines that linger, lines that fall away

```scheme
;; A poem where some lines fade after they arrive.
(define poem-with-fades
  '((:line \"The kitchen at dawn.\"                    :behavior stay)
    (:line \"Something on the stove.\"                  :behavior stay)
    (:line \"A jar of honey with a spoon in it.\"       :behavior fade-after 90)
    (:line \"Someone was here and left in a hurry.\"    :behavior stay)
    (:line \"You do not know when they will come back.\" :behavior fade-after 120)
    (:line \"You wait.\"                                 :behavior stay)))

(define (play-mixed-poem)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (let loop ((lines poem-with-fades) (i 0))
    (when (not (null? lines))
      (let* ((line (car lines))
             (text (node-get line :line))
             (beh  (node-get line :behavior))
             (fade-frames (node-get line :behavior-arg)))
        (paint-text-with-drop text 40 (+ 40 (* i 60)))
        (when (eq? beh 'fade-after)
          (world/after 90         ;; visible for a bit first
            (lambda ()
              (surface/dim 0.0 fade-frames))))
        (loop (cdr lines) (+ i 1))))))
```

The 'jar of honey' line arrives, is read, and fades. The reader is
left with the surrounding lines and the ghost of what was there. A
line that fades is a line she has to remember.

'You do not know when they will come back' — that line fades. The
next line is 'you wait.' The reader is reading 'you wait' while the
line that made her have to wait is disappearing above. That is a
poem, made playable.

Choose which lines fade with care. Fade a line that the reader
should hold in her mind while reading the next. Do not fade a line
that anchors the piece; the reader needs to keep it visible.

---

## 14.4 The spotlight

`surface/spotlight` draws attention to one word or phrase. Use it
sparingly — the equivalent of italic emphasis in prose.

```scheme
(define (spotlight-poem)
  (paint-text 40 100 \"You do not know when they will come back.\")
  ;; The word 'when' is spotlit — it is the pivot.
  (world/after 60
    (lambda ()
      (surface/spotlight 145 100 30 20 :duration 90))))
```

`surface/spotlight` draws a soft light on the given region for the
specified frames. The audience's eye goes there. The word 'when' is
now the emotional center of the line.

Do this once or twice per poem. Every line spotlit is no line
spotlit.

---

## 14.5 A poem in motion

Lines can move even after they arrive. A line about wind can drift
sideways. A line about weight can sink.

```scheme
;; Motion-based poem.
(define (motion-poem)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)

  ;; Line 1: sinks slowly.
  (paint-text 40 60 \"The stone in the pond.\")
  (motion/move-to 'line-1 40 200 :duration 300 :ease 'ease-in)

  ;; Line 2: floats up.
  (world/after 100
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 40 500 \"The ripple that was you.\")
      (motion/move-to 'line-2 40 350 :duration 240 :ease 'ease-out)))

  ;; Line 3: settles between them.
  (world/after 300
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 40 280 \"You do not always know which one you are.\")))
  )
```

The stone-line sinks (heavy, downward). The ripple-line rises (light,
upward). The third line sits between them, unmoving, weighted with
both. This is spatial arrangement as meaning.

You could write a whole book of poems where movement carries meaning.
Rain lines fall. Reunion lines drift together. Farewell lines drift
apart. The motion IS the poem.

---

## 14.6 Sound in a poem

Silence is fine. But a soft cue at the right moment lifts the whole
piece.

```scheme
(define (poem-with-sound)
  (audio/play 'wind-through-reeds :loop? #t :volume 0.15)   ;; a whisper of ambient

  (paint-text-with-drop \"The pond at first light.\"          40 60)
  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (audio/play 'water-drop :volume 0.3)
      (paint-text-with-drop \"A stone drops.\"                40 120)))

  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text-with-drop \"The ripples cross the whole face of it.\" 40 180)))

  (world/after 300
    (lambda ()
      (audio/halt 'wind-through-reeds)
      (paint-text-with-drop \"The pond does not look at itself.\"       40 240)))

  (world/after 420
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text-with-drop \"But it feels you.\"                        40 300)))
  )
```

Ambient wind for the first two-thirds. A water-drop cue when the
stone hits. Then silence — the ambient cuts on the fourth line. The
last line lands in absolute quiet.

The audience's ears have been full of soft wind for twelve seconds.
When it stops, the silence is loud, and the line 'but it feels you'
carries the whole poem's weight in the sudden quiet.

You cannot do that with a paper book.

---

## 14.7 A worked poem: The Kitchen

Here is a two-minute playable poem, complete.

```scheme
(define (the-kitchen)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (audio/play 'kettle-simmer :loop? #t :volume 0.2)

  (paint-text-with-drop \"You come in through the back door.\" 40 60)

  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text-with-drop \"The kettle is on.\" 40 110)))

  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text-with-drop \"There is a note on the counter in your\" 40 160)
      (paint-text-with-drop \"mother's handwriting.\"                    40 185)))

  (world/after 320
    (lambda ()
      (surface/spotlight 130 220 90 20 :duration 120)
      (paint-text-with-drop \"'Back soon.'\" 40 220)))

  (world/after 450
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text-with-drop \"You do not know when she wrote it.\" 40 270)))

  (world/after 570
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text-with-drop \"You do not know if she meant today.\" 40 310)))

  (world/after 690
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text-with-drop \"You put the kettle to full flame.\" 40 350)))

  (world/after 810
    (lambda ()
      (audio/play 'kettle-whistle :volume 0.4)
      (paint-text-with-drop \"The kettle whistles.\" 40 400)))

  (world/after 930
    (lambda ()
      (audio/halt 'kettle-simmer)
      (audio/halt 'kettle-whistle)
      (paint-text-with-drop \"You take it off. You wait.\" 40 450)))
  )
```

Ten lines. Two minutes. One ambient sound throughout, one specific
cue (the whistle), silence for the final line.

Read it out loud. Feel the pacing. 'You come in through the back
door.' Beat. 'The kettle is on.' Beat. The note. Spotlight on 'back
soon.' Two lines of not-knowing. The kettle whistles. Silence.
'You take it off. You wait.'

This is a piece somebody would read to a friend. Some friend would
cry. That is the game.

---

## 14.8 Common desktop tasks — a small daily ritual card

An operator writes a one-minute morning ritual card. Not a game, not a
poem, exactly. A small piece of pacing that helps her start the day.

```scheme
(define-card 'morning-ritual
  :init
  (lambda ()
    (scene/imagine)
    (surface/paper)
    (audio/play 'morning-birds :loop? #t :volume 0.2)

    (paint-text-with-drop \"morning.\" 40 60)

    (world/after 90
      (lambda ()
        (paint-text-with-drop \"the coffee.\" 40 110)))

    (world/after 180
      (lambda ()
        (paint-text-with-drop \"the list.\" 40 160)))

    (world/after 300
      (lambda ()
        (paint-text-with-drop \"one thing that matters today.\" 40 220)))

    (world/after 450
      (lambda ()
        (paint-text-with-drop
          (or (cortex/read 'today/one-thing)
              \"[type it here and press ENTER]\")
          40 280)))

    (world/after 600
      (lambda ()
        (paint-text-with-drop \"begin.\" 40 340)))
  ))
```

The operator opens this card first thing. Six lines arrive over ten
seconds. The fourth line asks her what matters today. She types it.
It saves to Cortex. The next line comes. 'Begin.'

Ten seconds. Every morning. Over months, the operator has a small
ritual that anchors her days. And a Cortex log of every 'one thing
that matters today' she has ever written. She can look back at it.

This is what a playable poem is for the operator. Small, quiet,
weighted with practice.

---

## 14.9 Routing patterns

**No branches.** Playable poems generally have no branches. One
path, controlled pace. Adding branches turns it back into a game.

**Short.** Under three minutes. Poems that go longer become slogs.
The reader loses the meditative state that made the piece work.

**Repeatable.** Design so that reading the poem twice is different
from reading it once. The reader who slows down on second pass
finds new spacing. The reader who speeds up finds the piece dense.

---

## 14.10 Closing

Playable poems are the outer edge of what narrative games can do.
They are also the easiest for a beginner to make well — no dialogue
trees, no camera work, no consequences. Just lines and pace.

Write one. Any topic. Ten lines. Play it for a friend. Ask her what
she felt. That is your feedback. Iterate.

Chapter 15 goes the opposite direction: long stories that survive
sessions. Save systems. Recaps. Sessions add up.")
